    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nI love neovim's default color theme. It looks very good with all programming languages I've tried. However, I noticed that markdown files in particular have almost no highlighting at all. It seems only bold text and Headings are highlighted using the bold text (same color still). The end result is a monochrome wall of text:\n\n<img width=\"784\" height=\"585\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/bdf0da59-6565-4d0a-8d73-81d76e27008f\" />\n\nI appreciate a lot the minimalist approach for the default color scheme (that's why I use it in the first place), but I think for markdown files in particular, a touch of color would be beneficial to make it easier to scan and read. In particular, the text of the headings, and maybe the bullet- and enumeration points (i.e. `*` and `1.` not the actual text), quotes and code blocks could be highlighted with an accent color.\n\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n* Headings: Bold with accent color\n* The fences of the fenced code blocks (e.g. ```python and ```) could be highlighted\n* The delimiters for lists (*, 1., etc.) could have highlighting\n* the blockquote delimiter (>) could have highlighting.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "You might want to try [tree-sitter](https://neovim.io/doc/user/treesitter.html) highlighting. It provides richer highlighting, more features, and supports language injections, which lets you achieve results like in the screenshot.\n\n<img width=\"1264\" height=\"832\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/ba62ff22-27b6-4f45-90d4-e3a4855c2775\" />\n\nNeovim already ships with a Markdown parser, so to enable it you just need:\n```lua\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"FileType\", {\n\tpattern = { \"markdown\" },\n\tcallback = function(ev)\n\t\tvim.treesitter.start(ev.buf)\n\tend,\n})\n```\nFor other languages, you'll need to install parsers via the [nvim-treesitter](https://github.com/nvim-treesitter/nvim-treesitter/tree/main) plugin. ",
